title: "Measuring Pulse Timing with STM32 Input Capture"
date: 2026-05-29
---

In this project, I built a pulse timing measurement tool on an STM32 microcontroller using timer input capture and UART-based interaction. The goal was to detect an incoming signal, measure the time between rising edges in microseconds, and summarize the distribution of measured pulse widths.

The core of the implementation uses **TIM2 input capture on Channel 1**. The program stores two consecutive capture values, computes their difference, and treats that difference as the pulse period in microseconds. Because the timer prescaler is set to 79, the timer runs at a 1 MHz tick rate on an 80 MHz clock, which makes each timer count equal to 1 microsecond. That makes the timing logic simple and easy to interpret.

Before starting the main measurement loop, the firmware performs a **power-on self-test (POST)**. It clears the timer counter, starts input capture, and waits briefly for a capture event. If a signal is detected, the system reports success over UART. If not, it prompts the user to retry or continue. This adds a practical validation step before data collection begins.

The application then interacts with the user over **UART2**. It prints the current lower and upper timing limits, gives the option to enter a new lower limit, and automatically sets the upper limit to 100 microseconds above it. By default, the valid timing window starts at 950 microseconds and ends at 1050 microseconds.

Once configured, the system begins capturing signals and collecting **1000 valid measurements**. For each completed pair of rising-edge captures, the code calculates the time difference and checks whether it falls inside the configured measurement window. If it does, the result is added into one of 101 histogram buckets, where each bucket corresponds to a specific microsecond value in the interval.

This histogram-style bucket array is a simple but effective way to summarize timing stability. Instead of only computing an average, the program shows how often each pulse width occurred. After 1000 accepted samples, the firmware stops input capture and prints the results as a time-versus-count table through UART.

A few implementation details make the design especially interesting:

- **Interrupt-driven capture:** edge timestamps are collected in the timer input capture callback.
- **Configurable timing window:** the user can tune the lower bound at runtime.
- **Microsecond resolution:** achieved through timer prescaler configuration.
- **Terminal-friendly reporting:** results are printed in a compact histogram table.

This project is a good example of combining embedded peripherals to build a focused measurement instrument. TIM2 provides precise hardware timing, UART2 provides a lightweight user interface, and the bucketed results make it easy to evaluate signal consistency.

If I were extending this project further, useful next steps would include handling timer counter rollover explicitly, adding debounce or noise filtering for unstable inputs, exporting results in CSV-style format, and allowing both lower and upper timing bounds to be configured independently.
